      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why B-Words Are Underrated</h2>
      <p>Many players overlook B because at 3 points it doesn't seem exciting. But B's real strength is its versatility. It pairs naturally with almost any vowel (BA, BE, BI, BO, BU) and leads into many common English word patterns. The BL-, BR-, and B-consonant clusters give you reliable access to medium-length words that score 15-25 points with premium square placement.</p>
      <p>B also serves as an excellent front hook. Words like LOCK become BLOCK, RIDGE becomes BRIDGE, and RING becomes BRING — adding points while creating a new word in the process.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">B-Word Strategy on the Board</h2>
      <p>To maximise your B-word scoring, keep these tactics in mind:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Pair B with Z for maximum impact:</strong> BIZ (14 pts) and BEZ (14 pts) are compact powerhouses. On a double-word square, BIZ becomes 28 points for three tiles.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use BOX strategically:</strong> BOX (12 pts) is common enough that most players don't challenge it, and the X landing on a premium square can yield 30+ points easily.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Remember BY as a parallel play helper:</strong> At just two letters and 7 points, BY fits alongside almost any existing word for bonus parallel scoring.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Front-hook aggressively:</strong> B is one of the best front-hook letters. Look for existing words that become new words with B added: EACH → BEACH, LOCK → BLOCK, LAST → BLAST.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't hold B too long:</strong> With only 2 in the bag, if you draw one, use it within a turn or two. Holding B waiting for the perfect spot often costs more in rack flexibility than it gains.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Essential Two-Letter B-Words</h2>
      <p>Two-letter words starting with B are critical for parallel plays and tight board situations:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>BA, BE, BI, BO, BY</strong> — the five valid two-letter B-words</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>BY</strong> (7 pts) is the highest scorer — the Y tile adds 4 points to B's 3</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>BI</strong> (4 pts) is underused — valid in both TWL and SOWPODS, it enables many parallel plays</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">B-Words With Bonus Tiles</h2>
      <p>The highest-scoring B-words combine B with other premium consonants. BUZZWORD uses both Z tiles and the W for a massive 32-point base. BEZIQUE pairs B with Z and QU for 27 points. Even without these extreme combinations, words like BOXCAR (17 pts) and BUXOM (16 pts) deliver strong returns from everyday tile draws.</p>
      <p>When you draw B alongside X, Z, J, or Q, immediately scan for these high-value combinations. The difference between a 12-point turn and a 30-point turn often comes down to knowing these words exist.</p>

